title: DIN Rail Mounted Open Top Bins

description.text: These bins are the first in a series of a modular storage system that I am designing around 35MM Type O DIN Rail. DIN Rail is widely available and comes in many different materials and finishes, Aluminum, Steel, Stainless Steel. Depending on what material and finish you select it can be had for around $2-$4 a meter and can be found at most industrial supply stores and online. You can find additional information about DIN Rail http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DIN_rail These bins are open top and simply snap on to the din rail. They require some cleanup after printing to remove the built-in supports at the ends and some cases the middle of the mounting area. The bins have a slot on the front that accepts a 30mm x 15mm tag for labeling. The bins were designed in Creo (Pro/Engineer) and the master files are included as a .zip file. Additional bin designs will be coming soon as well as a tool storage system.

• Print Bins with 0 extra shells
  • Remove Support Structure with Pocket Knife
  • Install on DIN Rail by Snapping in Place

description.text:
The world's first open source Rossler Attractor, with attractor-generating Mathematica notebook.

The Rossler Attractor is an attractor for the Rossler system, which is a system of three non-linear ordinary differential equations.

Strangely enough, this attractor was theorized, Otto Rossler, to be a part of the well known Lorenz attractor. Needless to say, this changed when Rossler saw the period in the z-axis.

Like the Lorenz attractor, the Rossler attractor is one of the few 'strange' attractors, which means that the attractor has fractal dimension.

For more information on how cool a Rossler Attractor is check out the wiki at https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rössler_attractor.

title: Printable Enclosure for Flicker-Hallucination Visor Electronics

description.text: This is a printable enclosure to go with the flicker-hallucination goggles ("brain machine") project. It was designed to fit the project shown on treehovse.blogspot.com.

I am posting the printable parts only here for personal archiving. We made these kits for a special event and have only a few left-over -- but you might be able to get one if you message me directly. These parts are designed to ( approximately ) fit these goggles : http://www.amazon.com/Welding-Goggles-Model-Code-Price/dp/B0025VMNHK/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1323018482&sr=8-1 I imagine that if you're familiar with hobby electronics, you will be able to modify the goggles similarly to as seen on treehovse.blogspot.com even without the kit. The idea is to sandwich RGB LEDs between translucent acrylic, approximately in front of each eye, and then make them blink in the 10-50Hz range with different color patterns. The button pad is printed in three sections : mask, buttons, and small-square-posts-that-contact-the-tactile-switches. These layers are super-glued together and then glued into the main enclosure. This button pad design has a good tactile feel and might be useful in other projects. Also of note : it turns out that if you print in light colored plastic, and make the walls thin, you can put indicator LEDs inside the enclosure and they will still shine through. Also of note : it may be possible to replace the acrylic diffuser with some sort of natural ABS / clear PLA printed object.

title: Ultifeeder the ultimate extruder feeder for your  Ultimaker 2

description.text:
Ok, I know... everybody has had their go at a version of the extruder feeder for the Ultimaker 2. I have used a customized version for a while and now there even is the UM2+ version as an upgrade available. So why another one...?

Well I personally like the Bondtech concept a lot where the filament is captured and driven from both sides. It gives less deformation on the filament, thus less friction in the bowden tube and less chance on grinding. Also I think it should be a very good option for flex filaments but I have not tested this personally. One note before you continue to read, although this is my 6th version with many tweaks, this is still a work in progress.

The good thing is that you can print all the parts and only need some cheap (eBay) gears and MR85 ball bearings which will set you back a whopping €10,-

Still interested?

Next to the printed parts you will need the following:

  • embedded bowden tube clamp : e.g. http://www.aliexpress.com/item/3D-printer-parts-accessory-1-4-tube-pipe-Embedded-Bowden-Couplings-For-3-00mm-Filament/32216034859.html
  • 2x mk8 drive gear 3mm : e.g. http://www.ebay.com/itm/141743511501
  • 2x 26 tooth drive gear : e.g. http://www.ebay.com/itm/381448621738
  • 3x MR85 ball bearing : e.g. http://www.ebay.com/itm/161808077922
  • 6x M3 x 20 hex bolts
  • 1x 3mm axle for the lever (27mm long)
  • 5mm axle for lever part (32.5mm long)
  • 5mm axle for extending the motor axle into the ball bearing (12mm long)
  • The original UM2 extruder spring
  • a small piece of bowden tube to fit in the lower opening of the base.

Notes:

I printed the case parts with 30% infill 0.1mm layer which is fine, the lever and pusher I did with 100% infill and 0.1mm layer height.

Only the lever needs support to build plate on in Cura, the rest is printed without support.
I added an internal support to the lever which can easily be removed by placing it on an opening and using a small driver to hit it from the top. The support can than be removed from the side. Also the pusher has support, if you push a sharp knife in the side where the gap is it can easily be removed.

Dash mount for Samsung Galaxy S6. This can be used as a stand alone cell phone holder or a smart dash mount. By utilizing the square slot for the placement of an NFC tag the mount gains the ability to launch apps and settings immediately as the phone is placed in the dash mount. In my case it launches an app called Drivemode, which is an app that simplifies the phones use so that the driver never needs to look at the phone to operate it. I needed a small-diameter nozzle for my shop vac so I could suck goop out of the nooks and crannies found around my shop. This nozzle fits on a fairly common after-market shop vac hose with an outside diameter of 45mm. It's available here The nozzle gives you an 8mm vacuum aperture which moves a lot of air but is reasonably small. This design requires a printer build envelope at least 80mm high.

This model is in two parts:  The adapter and the extender tube.  The adapter can be used alone, or the extension tube can be welded on if you want more reach.  
To make the combined unit, print both parts in ABS.  After cleaning them up, slip an 8mm drill bit into the extension tube and into the adapter to keep the two parts aligned (with the chamfered ends facing each other), then apply acrylic cement to the ends and clamp with the drill bit still in there.  
Unclamp after a couple of hours, remove the drill bit, and give your shop a good cleaning.

description.text:
PrintrBot Simple Metal Stability Feet

Author: Donald L. Merand for Explo

What Is It?

You ever use a PrintrBot Simple Metal without feet? Depending on how you've got your filament attached/balanced, they can be very easy to tip over. This is an attempt to fix that problem. It works okay!

Also, if you attach some non-slip rubber to the bottom of the feet, they act as a sound + vibration isolator and help to reduce resonant noise from the printer being amplified by the table it's sitting on.

How Do I Make One?

You have to print this diagonally on a PBSM, because it's wider than the print bed. If you're clever, you can print two at once. Two is all that you need.

It helps if you have some kind of non-stick thing under them. I've got some adhesive-backed rubber that I used. But it's optional.

What If I Have Needs?

I've made the model entirely parametric in OnShape over here, so feel free to copy it + hack away with your own needs.

Or you can ask me your question, and I'll be happy to answer it!

Please let me know if you make one, and happy printing!

description.text: raspberry 2 & 3 top, 40mm fan

This is a helmet from Megaman (The old NES game). At the current scale it is only a couple inches large, but I sliced it up in Tinkercad(I accidentally deleted those files) blew it up to 4.8x scale and it works as a cosplay helmet. If you like this you will probably like my podcast too, where I talk about all things geeky. New episodes every week http://www.fandompodcast.com Edit: I had a typo where I put Thingiverse where I should have put Tinkercad.

I printed at .3 with 2 perimeters and .08 infill.  I've added 2 files... one with a pad underneath it to help prevent warping and a single support so that I wouldn't have to turn supports on for my entire print for just one part. The second stl is of just the helmet in case anyone wants to slice it up so they can print it full size.  If anyone slices it into pieces I would love to see it posted as a derivative so that everyone can enjoy.
